<FONT CLASS="ArticleSource"><BIG>Editorial:</BIG></FONT> 
<FONT CLASS="ArticleHead"><BIG>Salt into the Wound</BIG></FONT>
<FONT CLASS="ArticleAuthorLight">&nbsp;filed by </FONT><FONT CLASS="ArticleAuthor">Faymar</FONT>
<DIV ALIGN=RIGHT>
<FONT CLASS=ArticleTime>10/05/2001 08:52 AM CDT</FONT>
<DIV ALIGN=LEFT>
<FONT CLASS=ArticleText>
I am stunned and amazed.<p>Y'all remember the idea of a European Fun Faire, the one where they picked some castle in the middle of nowhere supposedly in Paris, and then waited for everyone to book flights and hotels before saying &quot;Actually, thinking about it, we would much rather spend the weekend in Orlando.&quot;<p>Today I find, on my desk, an envelope from Sony Online Entertainment. &quot;What's this?&quot; I think, hoping for a map that is actually usable.<p>Inside is a note.<p><B>Greetings!<p>Thank you so much for your interest in attending the Paris Fan Faire. Again, we apologize for any inconvenience caused to you by the postponement of this event. Please accept this small token of our appreciation and we all hope that we will see you at a future Fan Faire.<p>Sincerely,<p>Cindy Archuleta<br>Community Relations Manager</B><p>They have sent me, in the most bizarre customer relations move yet, a baseball cap. Yes, a baseball cap. With the &quot;Everquest&quot; logo embroidered across it. I have not found <I>anyone</I> in my guild--100 people, all European--who would even consider wearing this cap if they had received it.<p>Do they really think I will feel better having been given the chance to advertise their product for free by putting this thing on my head? What do they appreciate, that I didn't quit the game in fury at the time? That I was fool enough to book things against their commitment to hold an event? That I've finally provided them a means of getting rid of that useless stock sitting around in their shop?<p>Now if they are going to bring this up again, the least they could do would be to try to show in some way that they actually value me as a customer, as opposed to some sort of walking signpost for them. A up-to-date map like they've done for Sullon Zek would be cool. A free copy of Shadows of Luclin would have made me ecstatic, especially if I actually got it in time to log in at launch, for once.<p>I won't even give this cap to my 7-year-old son to wear. I'm tempted to send one back with &quot;DAOC&quot; embroidered upon the front.<p><I><U>Moorgard adds:</U></I> While it's nice for Verant to make the gesture, I agree that something a little more substantial might have been done for the players who were affected by FanFaire's cancelation. A significant discount on Luclin or a free month of play would probably have been better received than a hat. Some who registered may have faced considerable financial penalties because the convention didn't happen.<p>The apology letter, of course, is a Good Thing(TM). Also, bear in mind that the cancelation wasn't necessarily all Verant's idea, as Ubi Soft (the company that distributes and <a href="http://www.eqloft.com/index.php">supports</a> EQ across the pond) played a part in organizing the Euro FanFaire. Still, a more timely response to such problems in the future would be a positive step in improving player/company relations.
</FONT>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
